This article discusses the Executive Order signed by President Barack Obama on March 16, 2012, titled "National Defense Resources Preparedness." The purpose of the order is to delegate authorities and address national defense resource policies and programs under the Defense Production Act of 1950. The order emphasizes the need for an industrial and technological base that can meet national defense requirements and contribute to the technological superiority of national defense equipment. It also highlights the importance of cooperation between the defense and commercial sectors for research and development. The order delegates authorities to various executive departments and agencies responsible for national defense planning and resource management. It establishes priorities and allocations authorities for certain agency heads to promote national defense over other contracts or orders. The order also addresses the expansion of productive capacity and supply, loan guarantees, loans, subsidies, and the development of substitutes for critical materials. It establishes the National Defense Executive Reserve (NDER), composed of individuals from the private sector and government who can be employed in executive positions during a national defense emergency. The order also establishes the Defense Production Act Committee, consisting of various agency heads, to advise the President on the effective use of authorities under the Act. The order includes definitions of key terms and revokes previous orders and regulations that are inconsistent with its provisions. The order emphasizes that it does not create any new rights or benefits enforceable against the United States.